  • You will practice decision trees on two datasets

Decision Trees Example - identify risky bank loans

Motivation

  • The global financial crisis of 2007-2008 highlighted the importance of transparency and rigor in banking practices

  • As the availability of credit was limited

    • banks tightened their lending systems
    • they turned to machine learning to more accurately identify risky loans

  • Decision trees are widely used in the banking industry due to

    • their high accuracy and ability to formulate a statistical model in plain language

  • Since governments in many countries carefully monitor the fairness of lending practices

    • executives must be able to explain why one applicant was rejected for a loan while another was approved
    • This information is also useful for customers hoping to determine why their credit rating is unsatisfactory

  • automated credit scoring models are used for credit card mailings and instant online approval processes

  • develop a simple credit approval model using C5.0 decision trees

  • see how the model results can be tuned to minimize errors that result in a financial loss

Decision Trees Example - identify risky bank loans

Step 1 - Motivation and dataset

  • Idea
    • credit model is to identify factors that are linked to a higher risk of loan default
    • data on past bank loans as well as information about the loan applicants that would have been available at the time of credit application
  • use the dataset containing information on loans obtained from a credit agency in Germany prepared by Hans Hofmann of the University of Hamburg

  • The Errors heading shows that the model correctly classified all but 108 of the 900 training instances for an error rate of 12%

  • A total of 39 actual no values were incorrectly classified as yes (false positives)

  • while 69 yes values were misclassified as no (false negatives)

  • Given the tendency of decision trees to overfit to the training data, the error rate reported here, which is based on training data performance, may be overly optimistic

library(rpart.plot)

# https://www.rdocumentation.org/packages/rpart.plot/versions/3.1.2/topics/rpart.plot

#pa_pal <- colorRampPalette(c("#A30664", "#E6B8D4", "#C6A1D1", "#A085CE", "#9FBBFC"))

pa_pal_2tone <- colorRampPalette(c("#DFBAD3", "#E6B8D4", "#BAD8F6", "#9FBBFC"))

credit_model2 %>% 
  extract_fit_engine() %>%
  #rpart.plot(box.palette = pa_pal_2tone(6),, type=1, extra=104, cex=0.38)
  rpart.plot(
    roundint = FALSE,
    box.palette = pa_pal_2tone(6),
    tweak = 1.2
  )
  • The complexity parameter (cp) in rpart is the minimum improvement in the model needed at each node
    • Itâs based on the cost complexity of the model defined as

\[ \sum\limits_{\text{Terminal Nodes}} \left( \text{Misclassification error} + \lambda \times \text{splits} \right) \]

  • The lambda is determined through cross-validation and not reported in R

  • The cp we see using printcp() is the scaled version of lambda over the misclassifcation rate of the overall data

  • The cp value is a stopping parameter

    • It helps speed up the search for splits because it can identify splits that donât meet this criteria and prune them before going too far

  • https://www.learnbymarketing.com/481/decision-tree-flavors-gini-info-gain/

  • https://www.learnbymarketing.com/tutorials/rpart-decision-trees-in-r/

Step 5 - improve model performance

  • modelâs error rate is likely to be too high to deploy it in a real-time credit scoring application

  • Predicting loan defaults using only 900 training examples seems to be a challenging problem

  • model performed especially poorly at identifying applicants who do default on their loans

  • we will leave it later

Boston housing data

It comes from a famous study on environmental economics by Harrison and Rubinfeld (1978)

Load the data

Code 
library(tidyverse)
library(tidymodels)
library(rpart.plot)
library(rpart)
library(vip)
library(caret)

boston<- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/kwan-MSDA/MSDA7003/refs/heads/main/Boston.csv")

boston<- boston %>% select(-c(1))
  • key variables
    • medv - median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s
    • crim - per capita crime rate by town
    • zn - proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.
    • indus - proportion of non-retail business acres per town
    • chas - Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)
    • nox - nitric oxides concentration (parts per 10 million)
    • rm - average number of rooms per dwelling
    • age - proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940
    • dis - weighted distances to five Boston employment centres
    • rad - index of accessibility to radial highways
    • tax - full-value property-tax rate per \(\$10,000\)
    • ptratio - pupil-teacher ratio by town
    • lstat - % lower status of the population

Specify the model

Code 
reg_tree_spec<- decision_tree() %>% 
  set_engine("rpart") %>%
  set_mode("regression")

fit the model

Code 
train<- boston %>% sample_frac(0.75)
test<- anti_join(boston, train)

reg_tree_fit<- reg_tree_spec %>% fit(medv~., data=train)

Prune the tree

Code 
prune<- reg_tree_fit %>% 
  extract_fit_engine() %>% 
  prune(cp=0.05)

prune %>% rpart.plot(extra=1, cex=0.8, digits=4)
Code 
library(rpart)
library(yardstick)
library(dplyr)

# Prune the tree
# Fit the regression tree
reg_tree_fit <- rpart(medv ~ ., data = train)

prune <- prune(reg_tree_fit, cp = 0.05)

# Make predictions on the test data
predictions <- predict(prune, newdata = test)

# Calculate the RMSE
rmse <- rmse_vec(truth = test$medv, estimate = predictions)
print(rmse)
